{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Bachay Ki Dua\" (\"A Child's Prayer,\" ch. 16) presents the parent-child relation from the child's end as an innocent, aspirational plea to God for a life of selfless light-bearing service.<sup>[1](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/#p-28b7ba)</sup> The line that most charges this relation—infusing it with poignant, self-sacrificial longing—is:  \n\n> O Lord, let my life be a moth's in its desire,  \n> To love the candle of knowledge, and draw ever nigher.<sup>[2](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/#p-01b332)</sup>  \n\nIn \"Maa ka Khwab\" (\"Mother's Dream,\" ch. 29), the relation is approached from the mother's end in a dream-vision of anxious, possessive love that hinders the child's path.<sup>[3](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4c138e)</sup> The line that most charges it—with raw reproach and emotional tension—is the mother's cry:  \n\n> You showed no care for me at all,  \n> and left. A fine devotion to recall!<sup>[4](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4c138e)</sup>  \n\nThese voices evoke **the same relationship**: the child's prayer seeks a luminous, independent destiny (moth to the candle of knowledge; life as candle flare), while the mother's dream reveals her tears extinguishing the son's lamp—symbolizing how clinging maternal love dims that very quest for light.<sup>[5](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4feffc)</sup><sup>[6](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/16-bachay-ki-dua/translation/#p-28b7ba)</sup> Iqbal pairs them thematically as ideal child-aspiration versus smothering parental attachment.",
